      <title>Challenge</title>
      <exercise>
        <!-- Kara's challenge problem -->
        <webwork>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Line <m>S</m> has the equation
              <m>y = ax + b</m> and Line <m>T</m> has the equation <m>y =cx + d</m>.
              Suppose <m> a \gt b \gt c \gt d \gt 0 </m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What can you say about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m>,
                    given that <m>a \gt c</m>?
                    Give as much information about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m> as possible.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <var form="essay"/>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What can you say about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m>,
                    given that <m>b \gt d</m>?
                    Give as much information about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m> as possible.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <var form="essay"/>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Since Line <m>S</m> has the equation
                    <m>y = ax + b</m> and Line <m>T</m> has the equation <m>y =cx + d</m>,
                    the variables <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> represent slopes.
                    Since <m> a \gt c \gt 0</m>,
                    we know that the slope of Line <m>S</m> is steeper than the slope of Line <m>T</m>.
                    We also know that both slopes are positive.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Since Line <m>S</m> has the equation
                    <m>y = ax + b</m> and Line <m>T</m> has the equation <m>y =cx + d</m>,
                    the variables <m>b</m> and <m>b</m> represent <m>y</m>-intercepts.
                    Since <m>b \gt d \gt 0</m>,
                    we know that Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m> both intersect the <m>y</m>-axis at positive <m>y</m>-intercepts and that Line <m>S</m> intersects the <m>y</m>-axis at a higher point than Line <m>T</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
